---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Section from "../components/Section.astro";

const title = "About — Odal Node";
const description =
  "Where Odal Node is built, who is building it, and how it relates to the European standards ecosystem.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <Section eyebrow="About" title="A small team, a public standard, and a long view.">
    <p>
      Odal Node is built in Skopje, North Macedonia, by a small team focused on
      one specific job: providing the open-source infrastructure that lets
      manufacturers comply with the EU Digital Product Passport requirements
      under the Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation. The project is
      deliberately scoped to that job. It is not a broad sustainability
      platform; it is not a generic supply-chain product; it is the regulatory
      compliance pipe for ESPR, no more and no less.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="Ecosystem" title="The standards bodies and pilot programmes the project works within." tone="muted">
    <p>
      The credibility of an open-source standard implementation comes from the
      ecosystem that recognises it. The project implements
      <strong>GS1 Digital Link 1.2</strong> for resolution, is applying for
      observer participation in <strong>CIRPASS-2</strong> — the EU project
      building out the Digital Product Passport ecosystem — and tracks the
      <strong>CEN/CENELEC JTC 24</strong> schema work, updating the relevant
      sector schemas as the standards bodies publish.
    </p>
    <p>
      These relationships are not endorsements. They are participation in the
      same conversations that produce the regulation the project implements.
      Being in the room matters when the regulation is written; staying in the
      room matters when it evolves.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="Positioning" title="A system of proof, not a system of record." tone="tinted">
    <p>
      Most compliance software is a <strong>system of record</strong>: the
      operator hands over their raw supply-chain data, and the vendor holds it,
      stores it, and must be trusted with it. Odal Node is a
      <strong>system of proof</strong>: the operator keeps the data and signs it
      locally; only the signed proof leaves their infrastructure. The difference
      is not a feature comparison — it is a different relationship to the
      operator's data, and it is the reason the architecture exists.
    </p>
    <p>
      That posture extends to competitors. The <code>dpp-core</code> library is
      Apache-2.0 and offered as a genuine starting point for the whole
      ecosystem — anyone, including a direct competitor, may build on it. A fork
      is welcome to the code; what a fork cannot copy is staying current with the
      regulation and operating the trust services. Those are earned, not
      licensed, and that is by design.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="Philosophy" title="Why the project is built the way it is.">
    <p>
      Two principles govern every architectural decision. The first is the
      <strong>proof-bound architecture</strong>: raw production data never enters
      Odal's systems. The manufacturer signs locally with their own key, and
      only the proof leaves their infrastructure — proof-bound describes the
      mechanism, not a promise. The second is the
      <strong>open-core boundary</strong>: code that implements regulation is
      Apache-2.0 in <code>dpp-core</code>; code that implements the commercial
      operational layer is BSL-1.1 in <code>dpp-engine</code>. These principles
      protect the credibility of the standard and the sustainability of the
      project at the same time.
    </p>
    <p>
      A longer treatment of both principles, with the architectural consequences
      drawn out, lives in
      <a href="https://docs.odal-node.io/design/proof-bound">the design principles section</a>
      of the documentation.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="Contact" title="How to reach the team." tone="muted">
    <p>
      General enquiries: <a href="mailto:hello@odal-node.io">hello@odal-node.io</a>.
      Security reports: <a href="mailto:security@odal-node.io">security@odal-node.io</a>
      (do not open public issues for vulnerabilities). Technical questions:
      <a href="https://github.com/odal-node/dpp-core/issues">GitHub Issues on dpp-core</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>
</Base>
